Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — simple string vs. complex object**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs
[RelayCommand]
async Task GoToDetails(Product product)
{
    // Approach A: pass just the ID as a query-string parameter
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");

    // Approach B: pass the full object via a dictionary
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        ["product"] = product
    });
}
```

**3. Receive data with `IQueryAttributable` on the target VM**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsViewModel.cs
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty] string productId;
    [ObservableProperty] Product product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: simple string parameter (comes in as string)
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
            ProductId = idObj.ToString();

        // Approach B: full object (comes in as the original type)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var prodObj) && prodObj is Product p)
            Product = p;
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the VM into the page**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Navigation call** | interpolated URI | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Received as** | `string` | original CLR type |
| **Survives deep-link / URI?** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (in-process only) |

Use **string parameters** for bookmarkable/deep-linkable routes. Use **object passing** when you already have the data loaded and want to avoid a redundant fetch.
